            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten, standing on a milk crate to see over the deli counter. His mother arrived with lunch, her insulated bag steaming. She set a container of pork and chive dumplings on the glass case, its warmth fogging the view of the mortadella. For a moment, the scent of hot peanut oil and ginger mingled with the sharp salt of pecorino. It wasn\u2019t a clash, but a perfect, unspoken harmony. That feeling became the blueprint for his life: finding the comforting balance in the blend.\n\n2.\nHe was in the SF State library, a marketing textbook open but unread, when his mom called. His father had taken a bad fall at the deli. There was no agonizing decision. He just shut the book, walked out of the library, and caught the MUNI to North Beach. The sudden, clarifying weight of responsibility felt more real and vital than any lecture. It taught him that his life\u2019s work would be measured in actions and loyalty, not in degrees or diplomas.\n\n3.\nThe day the deli closed, he and his father swept the floors together in near silence. The shelves were bare, the coolers dark. After locking the door for the last time, his father slumped against the glass, just for a second. Wei felt the immense weight of his quiet heartbreak. It wasn't just a business failure; it was the end of a world. That moment forged a new kind of resolve in Wei: to one day build something that honored that legacy, but couldn\u2019t be broken.\n\n4.\nA few years into managing the market, a young stocker named Leo messed up a big olive oil order and was terrified of being fired. Wei didn't yell. Instead, he told him about the time he\u2019d dropped an entire wheel of parmesan at his dad\u2019s shop. He saw the relief flood the kid\u2019s face. In that instant, Wei realized he wasn\u2019t just a manager; he was becoming the kind of boss he\u2019d always needed himself. That quiet success felt more meaningful than any sales report.\n\n5.\nHe was walking home through the Mission one evening, the sky that specific pink-orange of a San Francisco sunset. He passed a pop-up selling fresh pasta and, a block later, a woman selling jars of small-batch chili crisp from a folding table. It hit him then, a vision so clear it almost stopped him in his tracks. This was it. Not his father\u2019s deli, but a new story. \"Wei Rossi's\" wasn't just a vague dream anymore; it suddenly had a floor plan, a smell, and a soul."
